      <hedline>
        <hl1>Let the Fight Go On</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Steven A Ludsin letter comments on Howell Raines's August 23 Editorial Observer column on Vice Pres Al Gore's 'punchy language'</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Look Behind Al Gore's Punchy Language,'' by Howell Raines (Editorial Observer, Aug. 23):</p>
        <p>I thought Mr. Raines put his finger on the pulse of Al Gore's convention speech and his campaign strategy.  But I think it is unrealistic to believe that the fight mode of the presidential campaigns may prove tiresome to voters.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Look Behind Al Gore's Punchy Language,'' by Howell Raines (Editorial Observer, Aug. 23):</p>
        <p>I thought Mr. Raines put his finger on the pulse of Al Gore's convention speech and his campaign strategy.  But I think it is unrealistic to believe that the fight mode of the presidential campaigns may prove tiresome to voters.</p>
        <p>The post-convention bounce in Mr. Gore's poll numbers indicates that the pugilistic imagery struck a chord. The fighting words served Mr. Gore well by perpetuating the Democratic tradition of fighting for the underdog or disenfranchised.</p>
        <p>Campaigns by definition mean we agree to disagree, and a fight mode is healthy for an electorate that may be too complacent in good economic times.</p>
        <p>STEVEN A. LUDSIN  East Hampton, N.Y., Aug. 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
